<p>
Let \(V\) be a vector space
over either \(\mathbf R\) or \(\mathbf C\).
</p>
<p>
An <b>inner product</b> of \(V\) is a function
\(\langle\cdot,\cdot\rangle:V\times V\to\mathbf F\)
such that:
<ol>
<li>
The function is conjugate-symmetric:
\[\langle x, y\rangle = \overline{\langle y, x\rangle}.\]
</li>
<li>
The function is linear in the first argument:
\[\langle\alpha x + \beta y, z\rangle
= \alpha\langle x, z\rangle + \beta\langle y, z\rangle.\]
</li>
<li>
If \(x\ne 0\), then
\[\langle x, x\rangle = 0.\]
</li>
</ol>
</p>
<p>
An <b>inner product space</b> is a vector space
\(V\) with an inner product.
</p>
<p>
Related: facts about inner product spaces.
</p>
</body>
</html>
